column2: Description
This distinguishes the vehicle as all electric, plug-in hybrid, or hydrogen powered.
The 1st 10 characters of each vehicle's Vehicle Identification Number (VIN).
A unique identification number for each vehicle present in Transactions dataset. Transactions done on the same vehicle will have the same DOL Vehicle ID.
The model year of the vehicle, determined by decoding the Vehicle Identification Number (VIN).
The manufacturer of the vehicle, determined by decoding the Vehicle Identification Number (VIN).
The model of the vehicle, determined by decoding the Vehicle Identification Number (VIN).
This describes the primary intended use of the vehicle.
This tells how far a vehicle can travel purely on its electric charge.
The odometer value taken at the time of the Title Transaction.
The type of odometer value that was taken at the time of a Title Transaction.
If a vehicle is being sold by its manufacturer to its first owner, it is considered 'new'. Otherwise it is considered 'used'.
The amount that was reported to have been paid for a vehicle. A value of zero indicates that the sale price was not available.
The day on which the vehicle changed ownership.
This is the lowest Manufacturer's Suggested Retail Price (MSRP) for any version of the model in question.
The category of activity that was performed.
The day upon which a transaction was recorded into Department of Licensing's computer system.
The year upon which a transaction was recorded into Department of Licensing's computer system.
The County that the vehicle's owner is listed to reside within.
The City that the vehicle's owner is listed to reside within.
This describes the residential or business location of the primary vehicle owner.
The 5 digit zip code that the vehicle's owner is listed to reside within.
Shows if new vehicle title transactions were eligible for the sales tax exemption authorized by House Bill 2778 during the 2015 Legislative Session.

column1: 2019 HB 2042 Clean Alternative Fuel Vehicle (CAFV) Eligibility
column2: Shows if vehicle title transactions were eligible for the sales tax exemption authorized by House Bill 2042 during the 2019 Legislative Session.
True (or checked) = The vehicle model can travel 30 miles or more solely on electricity. Otherwise, False.
True (or checked) = The vehicle was sold on or after August 1, 2019. Otherwise, False.
True (or checked) = The vehicle sale price/value was $45,000 or less for new vehicles, or $30,000 or less for used vehicles. Otherwise, False.
This field displays ‘Meets battery range requirement’ if the vehicle model can travel 30 miles or more solely on electricity. Otherwise, it will display the reason why the requirement is not met.
This field displays ‘Meets purchase date requirement’ for title transactions for vehicles sold on or after August 1, 2019. Otherwise, it will display the reason why the requirement is not met.

This field displays ‘Meets title transaction requirement’ when the vehicle sale price/value was $45,000 or less for new vehicles, or $30,000 or less for used vehicles. Otherwise, it will display the reason why the requirement is not met.
The Electric Vehicle Fee is charged to some electric vehicles when they renew their registration. This indicates if it was collected during the transaction.
The Transportation Electrification Fee is charged to some electric vehicles when they renew their registration. This indicates if it was collected during the transaction.
The Hybrid Vehicle Electrification Fee is charged to some electric vehicles when they renew their registration. This indicates if it was collected during the transaction.

The census tract identifier is a combination of the state, county, and census tract codes as assigned by the United States Census Bureau in the 2020 census, also known as Geographic Identifier (GEOID). More information can be found here: https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/geography/about/glossary.html#par_textimage_13 https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/geography/guidance/geo-identifiers.html
The specific section of Washington State that the vehicle's owner resides in, as represented in the state legislature.

This is the electric power retail service territories serving the address of the registered vehicle. All ownership types for areas in Washington are included: federal, investor owned, municipal, political subdivision, and cooperative. If the address for the registered vehicle falls into an area with overlapping electric power retail service territories then a single pipe | delimits utilities of same TYPE and a double pipe || delimits utilities of different types. We combined vehicle address and Homeland Infrastructure Foundation Level Database (HIFLD) (https://gii.dhs.gov/HIFLD) Retail_Service_Territories feature layer using a geographic information system to assign values for this field. Blanks occur for vehicles with addresses outside of Washington or for addresses falling into areas in Washington not containing a mapped electric power retail service territory in the source data.
